<h1>ğŸ§© Implementation Guide</h1>

<h2>ğŸ–¥ï¸ Setting Up the VM (VirtualBox)</h2>

<p>
If you prefer to run this lab inside a virtual machine instead of directly on a Raspberry Pi, VirtualBox provides an easy and isolated environment for testing packet capture tools.
</p>

<h3>1. Download and Install VirtualBox</h3>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://www.virtualbox.org/">https://www.virtualbox.org/</a></li>
  <li>Install using default settings.</li>
</ul>

<h3>2. Download a Linux ISO</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Ubuntu Server</li>
  <li>Ubuntu Desktop</li>
  <li>Debian</li>
</ul>

<h3>3. Create a New Virtual Machine</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Name: <code>NetAnal-VM</code></li>
  <li>Type: Linux</li>
  <li>Version: Ubuntu (64-bit)</li>
  <li>Memory: 2â€“4 GB</li>
  <li>Disk: 20 GB dynamically allocated</li>
</ul>

<h3>4. Configure Networking</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Settings â†’ Network â†’ Adapter 1</li>
  <li>Bridged Adapter (recommended)</li>
  <li>Promiscuous Mode â†’ Allow All</li>
</ul>

<h3>5. Install Linux + Python 3.14</h3>
<pre><code>sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3.14 python3.14-venv python3.14-dev git
</code></pre>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ“¦ Setup & Installation</h2>

<h3>1. Clone the repository</h3>
<pre><code>git clone https://github.com/&lt;your-username&gt;/Cyber-Projects.git
cd Cyber-Projects/Network-traffic-analyzer
</code></pre>

<h3>2. Create a virtual environment</h3>
<pre><code>python3.14 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
</code></pre>

<h3>3. Install in editable mode</h3>
<pre><code>pip install --upgrade pip
pip install -e .
</code></pre>

<h3>4. Verify installation</h3>
<pre><code>netanal --help
</code></pre>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ“¡ Discovering Interfaces & Permissions</h2>

<h3>1. List interfaces</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal interfaces
</code></pre>

<h3>2. Check permissions</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal capture --help
</code></pre>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ§ Running a Basic Capture</h2>

<h3>1. Capture 50 packets</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal capture -i eth0 -c 50 --verbose
</code></pre>

<h3>2. What happens internally</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Builds <code>CaptureConfig</code></li>
  <li>Starts <code>CaptureEngine</code></li>
  <li>AsyncSniffer produces packets</li>
  <li>Consumer thread processes packets</li>
  <li>StatisticsCollector aggregates results</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ› Using BPF Filters</h2>

<h3>1. Capture only HTTP</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal capture -i eth0 --filter "tcp port 80" -c 50
</code></pre>

<h3>2. Programmatic filters</h3>
<pre><code>
builder = FilterBuilder().protocol(Protocol.HTTP).port(80)
expr = builder.build()
</code></pre>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ“Š Inspecting Statistics</h2>

<h3>1. Mixed traffic capture</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal capture -i eth0 -c 200
</code></pre>

<h3>2. Protocol distribution</h3>
<p>Generated by <code>print_protocol_table()</code> using:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>protocol_distribution</code></li>
  <li><code>protocol_bytes</code></li>
  <li><code>get_protocol_percentages()</code></li>
</ul>

<h3>3. Top talkers</h3>
<p>Driven by endpoint and conversation tracking in <code>statistics.py</code>.</p>

<hr />

<h2>ğŸ“ˆ Bandwidth & Performance</h2>

<h3>1. Long capture</h3>
<pre><code>sudo netanal capture -i eth0 -c 1000
</code></pre>

<h3>2. Behavior</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Bounded queue prevents memory blowup</li>
  <li>Locks ensure accurate counters</li>
  <li>BPF reduces CPU load</li>
</ul>
